04563nam a22006735i 9780804794527DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047945277 a10.1515/97808047945272doi  a(DE-B1597)564299  a(OCoLC)1178769364  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aJQ1809 7aPOL0070002bisacsh04a306.20089/94350431551 aTuram, Berna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGaining Freedoms :bClaiming Space in Istanbul and Berlin /cBerna Turam. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tACRONYMS -- tINTRODUCTION. The City and the Government -- t1. BETWEEN STATE SPACES AND AUTONOMOUS PLACES -- t2. A NEIGHBORHOOD DIVIDED BY LIFESTYLES -- t3. AFFINITIES IN THE ZONES OF FREEDOM -- t4. FAULT LINES ON CAMPUS -- t5. NEW COALITIONS IN SAFE ZONES -- t6. KREUZBERG'S DIVIDED DIASPORA -- t7. EMERGING SOLIDARITIES IN IMMIGRANT ZONES -- tCONCLUSION. Unified Opposition to the Divided Supremacy of the AKP -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGaining Freedoms reveals a new locus for global political change: everyday urban contestation. Cities are often assumed hotbeds of socio-economic division, but this assessment overlooks the importance of urban space and the everyday activities of urban life for empowerment, emancipation, and democratization. Through proximity, neighborhoods, streets, and squares can create unconventional power contestations over lifestyle and consumption. And through struggle, negotiation, and cooperation, competing claims across groups can become platforms to defend freedom and rights from government encroachments. Drawing on more than seven years of fieldwork in three contested urban sites-a downtown neighborhood and a university campus in Istanbul, and a Turkish neighborhood in Berlin-Berna Turam shows how democratic contestation echoes through urban space. Countering common assumptions that Turkey is strongly polarized between Islamists and secularists, she illustrates how contested urban space encourages creative politics, the kind of politics that advance rights, expression, and representation shared between pious and secular groups. Exceptional moments of protest, like the recent Gezi protests which bookend this study, offer clear external signs of upheaval and disruption, but it is the everyday contestation and interaction that forge alliances and inspire change. Ultimately, Turam argues that the process of democratization is not the reduction of conflict, but rather the capacity to form new alliances out of conflict.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aPolitical participationxPolitical aspectszTurkeyzIstanbul. 0aPublic spacesxPolitical aspectszTurkeyzIstanbul. 0aPublic spaceszGermanyzBerlin. 0aSocial conflictzGermanyzBerlin. 0aSocial conflictzTurkeyzIstanbulxPolitics and government. 0aTurkszGermanyzBerlin. 4aauthoritarianism. 4acampus. 4acity. 4ademocratization. 4afreedoms. 4agovernment. 4aneighborhood. 4apolitics. 4arights. 4aurban space. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political ideologies / Democracy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311070398640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479452740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804794527423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804794527.jpg  a978-3-11-070398-6  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles